'''Kagemand''' is a Danish cake shaped like a girl or boy<ref name="TG">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Happy birthday, Gen Z: celebrating with 16-year-olds around the world |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/dec/10/happy-birthday-generation-z-16-around-the-world |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[U.K.]] |date=10 December 2016 |access-date=12 December 2016}}</ref> which is traditionally eaten at birthdays and anniversaries.<ref>{{cite news |last=Vendelbjerg |first=Lars |date=27 August 2015 |title=Bager lavede fem meter høj kagemand  |trans-title=A baker made a 5-metre long kagemand |url=http://dagbladet-holstebro-struer.dk/holstebro/Bager-lavede-fem-meter-hoej-kagemand/artikel/23556 |language=Danish |newspaper=Holstebro Struer Dagbladet |location=[[Holstebro]], [[Denmark]] |access-date=12 December 2016}}</ref><ref name="TG"/> 

The cake is usually made with either a soft yeast dough topped with [[brown sugar]] or a [[Danish pastry]] dough topped with icing glacé. In any case, the cake is decorated with candy and festive Danish flags. Traditionally, the birthday party starts with the cake figure being [[decapitation|decapitated]] or dismembered, while all the children scream.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-great-british-bake-off/on-demand/67644-008 |work=[[The Great British Bake Off]] |author=[[Sandi Toksvig]] |title=Episode 8 - Danish week |date=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{citation |work=Celebrating Life Customs around the World |volume=Baby Showers to Funerals |title=Birthday cakes, international |author=Victoria Williams |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2016 |isbn=9781440836596 |page=35}}</ref>

