{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}

The '''Party for Renewal and Development''' ({{lang-pt|Partido para Renovação e Desenvolvimento}}, PRD) was a political party in [[Guinea-Bissau]].

==History==
The PRD was established on 12 February 1992 by dissidents from the Group of 121 who had been urging reform of the ruling [[African Party for the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde|PAIGC]], and was initially led by [[João da Costa]].<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p319</ref> It joined the [[Union for Change]] alliance prior to the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1994|1994 general elections]], with the Alliance winning six seats in the [[National People's Assembly (Guinea-Bissau)|National People's Assembly]], of which the PRD took one.<ref name=HD/>

Following the death of da Costa, [[Manuel Rambout Barcellos]] became party leader.<ref name=HD/> The Union was reduced to three seats in the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1999–2000|1999–2000 general elections]], and lost them all in the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]], after which the PRD became inactive.<ref name=HD/>

